+\paragraph{A two-grid local Fourier analysis} The ceiling $\rho\approx\tfrac12$ and its removal by
+caliber-2 can be \emph{derived}, not only measured. On the constant-coefficient model---strong weight
+$1$ along $x$, weak weight $\epsilon$ along $y$ on $\mathbb Z^2$---the Laplacian acts on the grid mode
+$\varphi_\theta(\mathbf m)=e^{\mathrm{i}\,\theta\cdot\mathbf m}$ with symbol
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:Lsymbol}
+\hat L(\theta)=4\sin^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}+4\epsilon\sin^2\tfrac{\theta_y}{2},
+\qquad \theta=(\theta_x,\theta_y)\in(-\pi,\pi]^2 .
+\end{equation}
+As $\epsilon\ll1$, $\hat L(\theta)$ is small exactly when $\theta_x\approx0$ for \emph{any} $\theta_y$:
+the algebraically smooth error is smooth along the strong axis but unconstrained across the weak one.
+Affinity therefore semicoarsens $2{:}1$ in $x$ and keeps every $y$-line---the correct coarsening, since
+full $y$-resolution represents the $\theta_y$-oscillatory slow modes (Fig.~\ref{fig:semicoarsen}).
+
+\emph{Harmonics.} The $2{:}1$ $x$-coarsening folds each low mode $\theta$
+($\theta_x\in(-\tfrac\pi2,\tfrac\pi2]$) with its $x$-harmonic
+$\theta^{\ast}=(\theta_x{+}\pi,\,\theta_y)$; the pair spans a subspace invariant under the two-grid
+operator, on which the operator is the $2\times2$ matrix
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:tgsymbol}
+\hat M(\theta)=\hat S(\theta)^{\nu}\Big[\,I-\hat P\,(\hat P^{\ast}\hat L\hat P)^{-1}\hat P^{\ast}\hat L\,\Big],
+\qquad \hat L=\mathrm{diag}\big(\hat L(\theta),\hat L(\theta^{\ast})\big)=:\mathrm{diag}(\ell_1,\ell_2),
+\end{equation}
+with $\hat S$ the smoother symbol, $\nu$ the number of pre-smoothings, $\hat P\in\mathbb C^{2\times1}$
+the interpolation symbol, Galerkin coarse symbol $\hat L_c=\hat P^{\ast}\hat L\hat P$, and variational
+restriction $\hat R=\hat P^{\ast}$. The bracketed coarse-grid correction is the $\hat L$-orthogonal
+projector \emph{off} $\mathrm{range}\,\hat P$, hence idempotent with spectrum $\{0,1\}$: correction
+alone does not converge---the smoother must remove whatever the coarse space omits.
+
+\emph{Interpolation symbols.} Write $s=\sin^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}$, $c=\cos^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}$
+($s{+}c=1$). Interpolating the fine point midway between two coarse parents has the symbol (up to a
+unimodular phase that cancels in \eqref{eq:tgsymbol})
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:Psymbols}
+\hat P_{\mathrm{c1}}\propto\begin{pmatrix}\cos\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\\[2pt]\mathrm{i}\,\sin\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\end{pmatrix}
+\ \ (\text{caliber-1, piecewise constant}),\qquad
+\hat P_{\mathrm{c2}}=\begin{pmatrix}c\\ s\end{pmatrix}\ \ (\text{caliber-2, linear}).
+\end{equation}
+The decisive difference is the \emph{harmonic} (second) component as $\theta_x\to0$: it is $O(\theta_x)$
+for caliber-1 but $O(\theta_x^2)$ for caliber-2. Caliber-2 injects asymptotically no energy into the
+unresolved harmonic of a smooth mode---the order-$2$ interpolation property \cite[\S4.3]{guide}.
+
+\emph{The factor.} The correction in \eqref{eq:tgsymbol} is a rank-one projector, so $\det\hat M=0$
+and the spectral radius equals the trace:
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:rhotrace}
+\rho\big(\hat M(\theta)\big)=\big|\,\hat S(\theta)^{\nu}(1-\beta)+\hat S(\theta^{\ast})^{\nu}\,\beta\,\big|,
+\qquad
+\beta=\frac{|\hat P_1|^2\,\ell_1}{|\hat P_1|^2\,\ell_1+|\hat P_2|^2\,\ell_2}\in[0,1],
+\end{equation}
+where $\beta$ is the fraction of the interpolant's $\hat L$-energy carried by the smooth harmonic and
+$q:=1/\beta$ is the local-mode form of the per-node energy ratio \eqref{eq:guard}. Substituting
+\eqref{eq:Psymbols} and letting $\epsilon\to0$,
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:betas}
+\beta_{\mathrm{c1}}=\tfrac12\ \ (q=2)\quad\text{for every }\theta_x,
+\qquad
+\beta_{\mathrm{c2}}=\cos^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\to1\ \ (q\to1)\ \text{ as }\theta_x\to0 :
+\end{equation}
+caliber-1 commits exactly half of every interpolant's energy to the wrong harmonic, caliber-2 a
+vanishing fraction on the smooth modes.
+
+\emph{The ceiling.} For the explicit $\omega$-Jacobi smoother
+$\hat S(\theta)=1-\tfrac{\omega}{2(1+\epsilon)}\hat L(\theta)$ with $\omega=\tfrac12$ (which annihilates
+the highest $x$-mode, $\theta_x=\pi$), the $\epsilon\to0$ symbols are
+$\hat S(\theta)=\cos^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}$ and $\hat S(\theta^{\ast})=\sin^2\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}$. With
+$\beta_{\mathrm{c1}}=\tfrac12$, \eqref{eq:rhotrace} gives
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:c1ceiling}
+\rho_{\mathrm{c1}}(\theta)=\tfrac12\big(\cos^{2\nu}\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}+\sin^{2\nu}\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\big),
+\qquad \sup_{\theta}\rho_{\mathrm{c1}}=\tfrac12\quad\text{for every }\nu\ge1,
+\end{equation}
+the supremum attained as $\theta_x\to0$. The maximizing modes are \emph{smooth in $x$}, where any local
+smoother is powerless ($\hat S(\theta)\to1$); hence $\rho_{\mathrm{c1}}\ge\tfrac12$ for \emph{any} local
+smoother and any number of sweeps---an irreducible $\rho=1-1/q=\tfrac12$ ceiling set by the
+interpolation, with equality for real-symbol smoothers such as $\omega$-Jacobi and red--black GS.
+Caliber-2 instead has $\beta\to1$ on those same smooth modes, relocating the residual onto the
+$x$-harmonic at $\theta_x=\tfrac\pi2$, a genuinely high-frequency, smoothable mode:
+\begin{equation}\label{eq:c2textbook}
+\rho_{\mathrm{c2}}(\theta)=\cos^{2\nu}\!\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\,\sin^2\!\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}
++\sin^{2\nu}\!\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}\,\cos^2\!\tfrac{\theta_x}{2}
+\ \Longrightarrow\
+\sup_{\theta}\rho_{\mathrm{c2}}=\big(\tfrac12\big)^{\nu}\ (\nu\le3),\ \ O(1/\nu)\to0 .
+\end{equation}
+At the operative $\nu=2$ this reads $\rho_{\mathrm{c1}}=\tfrac12$ versus $\rho_{\mathrm{c2}}=\tfrac14$,
+consistent in magnitude and mechanism with the per-level split measured under Gauss--Seidel
+($0.46\!\to\!0.28$, \S\ref{sec:cal2})---the exact Gauss--Seidel constants differ because its symbol is
+complex, unlike the analytic Jacobi model. Raising $\gamma$ and recombination bound the caliber-1 value
+into the multilevel rate of Table~\ref{tab:aniso} but cannot pass it, whereas caliber-2 needs no such crutch.
+
+\emph{Scope.} The analysis is constant-coefficient: it proves caliber-2's textbook efficiency on a
+\emph{correctly} semicoarsened grid, and so justifies raising the caliber by the interpolation-order
+rule \cite[\S4.3]{guide} rather than by experiment. It does not see the finite-sample affinity
+inversion of \S\ref{sec:soc}, which corrupts the coarsening itself on an unlucky test-vector sample;
+the strength-of-connection veto is what secures the clean semicoarsening this analysis assumes, so the
